def: The upper lip or helmet-shaped part of a labiate flower.
Without a seam.Christ's seamless coat, all of a piece. Jer. Taylor.

One who, or that which, sinks. Specifically:(a) A weight on something, as on a fish line, to sink it.(b) In knitting machines, one of the thin plates, blades, or otherdevices, that depress the loops upon or between the needles. Dividingsinker, in knitting machines, a sinker between two jack sinkers andacting alternately with them.-- Jack sinker. See under Jack, n.-- Sinker bar. (a) In knitting machines, a bar to which one set ofthe sinkers is attached. (b) In deep well boring, a heavy bar forminga connection between the lifting rope and the boring tools, above thejars.
The lower chaps or jaw. Paley.
The class of skin disease developed by the dartrous diathesis.See under Dartrous.
Wolfram, an ore of tungsten. Simmonds.
Pertaining to, or situated near, the back, or dorsum, of ananimal or of one of its parts; notal; tergal; neural; as, the dorsalfin of a fish; the dorsal artery of the tongue; -- opposed toventral.
Having the organs or parts of one side correspponding withthose of the other; having the parts in two or more series of organsthe same in number; exhibiting a symmetry.See Symmetry, 2.

A contrivance or arrangement serving as a fulcrum for an oar inrowing. It consists sometimes of a notch in the gunwale of a boat,sometimes of a pair of pins between which the oar rests on the edgeof the gunwale, sometimes of a single pin passing through the oar, orof a metal fork or stirrup pivoted in the gunwale and suporting theoar.
The state of being co√∂rdinate; equality of rank or authority.

That which occasions distress, trouble, or vexation; severeaffliction.When tribulation or persecution ariseth because of the word, by andby he is offended. Matt. xiii. 21.In the world ye shall have tribulation. John. xvi. 33.
